h, MA, from Kent, England, in the 1620s; <i>c.</i> 1650 he moved to Duxbury and subesequently to Bridgewater. He had many prominent descendants, among them one of the earliest families on Martha's Vineyard. — The surname <i>Bassett</i> of French origin (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessette","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Armand, Adrien, Normand, Alphonse, Lucien, Cecile, Herve, Jacques, Laurent, Aime.","French: topographic name designating a small wood of birches, from Occitan <i>bès</i> ‘birch tree’ (see   Besse  ), or a habitational name from (La) Bessette, the name of several places in the southern part of France.","Alternatively, an altered form of French <b>Besset</b>: topographic name, a cognate of 1 above. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Pynchard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","from the Old Norman French personal name <i>Ponchard</i>, Old French <i>Ponsard</i>, a pet form of <i>Ponce</i> (see   Points  ).","habitational name from Pontchardon (in Orne, France), whose name means ‘thistle bridge’."],"variants":[{"name":"Points","meanings":["English (of Norman origin):","from the Old French personal name <i>Ponz</i>, <i>Ponce</i>, from Latin <i>Pontius</i> (see   Ponce  ).","habitational name from any of several places called Ponts (such as those in Manche and in Seine-Maritime, Normandy), from Latin <i>pontes</i> ‘bridges’. This name has been established since the 13th century in Ireland, where it appears as <i>Pounce</i> and <i>Pounche</i>, and is Gaelicized as <b>Púinse</b>."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":82,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir John Pynchard Bassett 1st Lord of Uley was born about 1300, in Uley, Gloucestershire, England, his father, Sir Anselme Bassett, was 30 and his mother, Margaret De Berkeley, was 27. He married Isabella Ettington Maynell in 1330, in Uley, Gloucestershire, England. 